Aug 21 2006	Great for the price!	If you're looking for a luxury hotel, this isn't the place. But if you want a clean, respectable budget hotel this one is worth looking at. Although in an older building with a very small, slow elevator, the rooms have been nicely updated and are fairly spacious. The bed was very comfortable, the maid service was acceptable, and we saw no bugs of any kind in the room or the washrooms. Our television and air-conditioner were almost brand new, although the latter was fairly noisy it worked extremely well on hot summer nights. The shared washrooms were also newly renovated and seemed surprisingly clean, although some careless guest clogged a toilet which had some unsanitary consequences. The number of shared washrooms was sufficient, and we rarely had to wait to get in one, even though the hotel was full. The clientele was largely European, but all seemed respectable -- this is not like a downtown YMCA or anything. The neighbourhood seemed quite reasonable, and we encountered no problems even walking the streets in the wee hours of the morning. It was only 1 1/2 blocks from the subway and 3-4 blocks from Central Park. Times Square was only about 4 subway stops away if you take the express trains 2 or 3, and about 6-7 stops on the the local train - 1. Near the subway stop you could find everything you need from restaurants (try the Key West diner), grocery stores (The Food Emporium), pharmacies, Starbucks, MacDonald's and liquor/wine stores (all within a 4-5 block area along Broadway between 92nd and 97th streets). Not only convenient, the neighborhood seems very safe. We would highly recommend this hotel to anyone that doesn't mind shared bathrooms and the European pensione-style hotel (We paid $75.00 US$ per night all taxes included through Expedia, although for a higher price you could have a private bathroom).	
